In .NET MAUI, use the **lifecycle mapping events** on `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` in your `MauiProgram.cs`:

```csharp
using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;

public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
{
    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>
    {
#if ANDROID
        events.AddAndroid(android => android
            .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android OnPause */ })
            .OnStop(activity =>  { /* runs on Android OnStop  */ }));
#endif

#if IOS
        events.AddiOS(ios => ios
            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS DidEnterBackground */ }));
#endif
    });

    return builder.Build();
}
```

**Key points:**

- `ConfigureLifecycleEvents` is the single entry point for all platform lifecycle hooks.
- `AddAndroid` / `AddiOS` expose the native events (`OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnResume`, `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, etc.).
- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives so the platform-specific code only compiles for its target.
- The callbacks receive the native object (`Activity` on Android, `UIApplication` on iOS), so you can call platform APIs directly if needed.
